2019-12-16 02:15:56	OneSploit	8G
2019-12-16 02:16:20	OneSploit	I mean it can be 16G its cloud node
2019-12-16 02:16:45	<--	milkt (~debian@gateway/tor-sasl/milkt) has quit (Client Quit)
2019-12-16 02:16:54	OneSploit	but files were initially in CSV, so I decided to use parquet for multi-threaded reading and fast index based access.
2019-12-16 02:17:06	-->	milkt (~debian@gateway/tor-sasl/milkt) has joined #python
2019-12-16 02:17:15	-->	operateur (~operateur@91.143.220.230) has joined #python
2019-12-16 02:17:33	OneSploit	I am just not sure if pyarrow.read_table is loading the whole thing into memory or caching it
2019-12-16 02:17:35	energizer	parquet is fine for big datasets, but if you're going to manipulate the dataframe you will want to have *at least* twice as much ram as the file on disk
2019-12-16 02:18:15	-->	davepdotorg (~davepdoto@2a00:23c5:bec3:4700:b0f1:2e12:2b2:de3c) has joined #python
2019-12-16 02:18:17	energizer	because when you transform the data you'll often end up having two copies in memory during the process
