2019-12-16 04:10:58	Falc	ramsub071: well, you can't slice a dict... But I can sort of understand what you're after...
2019-12-16 04:11:08	[Tritium]	You would have to make a sequence type (list(your_dict.items())) of pairs, and you can slice that
2019-12-16 04:11:36	ramsub071	it shouldn't be a dict afterall, i guess
2019-12-16 04:12:05	ramsub071	[Tritium]: yes,but how do i choose the nearest value of key if the key is absent ?
2019-12-16 04:12:12	-->	grumble (~grumble@freenode/staff/grumble) has joined #python
2019-12-16 04:12:20	Falc	ramsub071: if you want it to be a dict, you can use a range() to go over the actual ints, and than use a failsafe dict get operation
2019-12-16 04:12:49	ramsub071	Falc: what is a failsafe dict get
2019-12-16 04:13:47	Falc	ramsub071: dict[missing_key] raises an error, there's a number of ways to get a value from a dict without failing (dict.get, defaultdict, try/except, ...)
2019-12-16 04:14:02	-->	chewyDelicious (~nooblet@musketeer-63.fusion.uni-jena.de) has joined #python
2019-12-16 04:14:17	[Tritium]	you can probably manage something with heapq... but ultimately, if i had that problem, i would run parallel datastructures - store the items as pairs in a heapq, and keep a dict of key:index .... or something.  most people in here are better at algorithms than me.
2019-12-16 04:14:45	Falc	ramsub071: so the idea is to iterate over ints, say from 0 to 10, and by using failsafes you'd be guaranteed to only select actually existing keys
