2019-12-16 16:43:17	SnoopJeDi	I don't understand the problem, then. In Py3 `"hello\xa0there".split()` should return `['hello', 'there']`
2019-12-16 16:43:22	cdunklau	Trynix: .split('\xa0')
2019-12-16 16:43:28	cdunklau	SnoopJeDi: they're doing .split(' ')
2019-12-16 16:43:35	SnoopJeDi	oh
2019-12-16 16:43:51	SnoopJeDi	Well, just use .split() then, and you get lots of whitespace-aware behavior for free :)
2019-12-16 16:43:58	cdunklau	yep
2019-12-16 16:44:13	cdunklau	Trynix: so if you just want to split on *runs* of any whitespace, .split() (no args)
2019-12-16 16:44:20	Trynix	oooo
2019-12-16 16:44:24	Trynix	that worked
2019-12-16 16:44:28	Trynix	thanks alot!!
2019-12-16 16:44:29	SnoopJeDi	N.b. that this includes newlines
