2019-12-16 19:40:33	tharkun	How can I figure out which version of python is the underlying system using?
2019-12-16 19:41:22	papna	tharkun: underlying system?
2019-12-16 19:41:27	papna	tharkun: Possibly:      python -V
2019-12-16 19:41:31	tharkun	I do not want to mess with it since I might as well require some extra modules that can conflict with it.
2019-12-16 19:42:59	tharkun	2.7.13 thanks. IIRC there is a way to install different versions of python and use them in a type of jail Can you slap me on the right direction?
2019-12-16 19:43:28	energizer	tharkun: "virtual environment"
2019-12-16 19:43:41	grym	tharkun: i recommend that you install a python interpreter, or more than one, with pyenv - and then make a virtual environment from that
2019-12-16 19:44:14	grym	tharkun: (particularly because pyenv lets you install modern pythons on many systems that don't have it available in package managers)
2019-12-16 19:44:24	InPhase	tharkun: If it's numerical work, conda is the one you want.
2019-12-16 19:44:45	grym	InPhase: i rarely need it
2019-12-16 19:45:10	grym	miniconda can be very, very handy on windows though
2019-12-16 19:45:11	energizer	tharkun: if you are starting a project i suggest using poetry (http://python-poetry.org/ `poetry new --src myproject`) and if you're just installing command line tools i suggest using pipx (https://pipxproject.github.io/). these will create and manage the virtualenvs for you, much easier
2019-12-16 19:45:25	InPhase	grym: Right, it just seems to be where a cultural divide has fallen.
2019-12-16 19:46:04	offby1	energizer: https://pipxproject.github.io/pipx/ apparently
