2019-12-16 20:39:50	energizer	just make a database and use it
2019-12-16 20:39:55	offby1	very_sneaky: I'm with you here.  What I tend to do is write the "business logic" -- the functions that need careful testing -- to work only with Python objects, like say lists of dicts; those can be tested without a database.  Then of course you need functions that create those objects from the db, and write them back to the db; but those will have very little logic, and can be tested with other ("integration") tests
2019-12-16 20:40:11	very_sneaky	I've achieved something similar in java's spring jpa using the @AutoConfigureTestDatabase annotation, which i think uses a h2 backend
2019-12-16 20:40:17	-->	kdc (~kdc@196.211.197.147) has joined #python
2019-12-16 20:40:20	energizer	if you're doing logic why do you need to mock anything, just pass the data in to the function
2019-12-16 20:40:49	offby1	if you're lucky, you can get (say) sqlalchemy to write those latter functions for you, so you don't have to test them beyond "smoke" (i.e., run one of them once to make sure you're really connecting to the database, etc)
2019-12-16 20:41:05	very_sneaky	@energizer honestly i'm at the beginning of dev here, i'm trying to take a more TDD approach so I can literally design it however is best, my first thought was to mock the session object though
2019-12-16 20:41:09	Mrbuck	grym: okay I am using number typed them for example..I checked the doument you referred I dont want to copy from x but manipulate x and generate array out of it like x[i][1] < x[i][2]
2019-12-16 20:41:33	grym	Mrbuck: np.array takes a list as an argument and returns a numpy array
2019-12-16 20:41:39	energizer	def main(db): data = db.get_data(); new_data = do_logic(data); db.update(new_data)
2019-12-16 20:41:58	grym	Mrbuck: there are also convenience methods for creating arrays of a given size from zeroes and ones and noise
2019-12-16 20:42:09	grym	and random numbers from various distributions
2019-12-16 20:42:49	grym	Mrbuck: so it's np.array(x), from  your example above, like it says in the docs :D
