2019-12-17 00:49:41	client35	I've been reading over the docs, but one thing is unclear to me, when should I actually use NotImplemented? https://docs.python.org/3.7/library/constants.html#NotImplemented
2019-12-17 00:49:42	<--	i9zO5AP (~BQcdf9eiZ@41.248.193.64) has quit (Ping timeout: 246 seconds)
2019-12-17 00:50:03	client35	I'm coding for user input and if they input something wrong, I need to throw an exception
2019-12-17 00:50:52	client35	Maybe ValueError?
2019-12-17 00:51:10	energizer	don't confuse NotImplemented with NotImplementedError
2019-12-17 00:51:26	-->	moonshine_ (~moonshine@112.134.105.118) has joined #python
2019-12-17 00:51:51	energizer	NotImplemented is for the left side of a binary operator, like if you're implementing __add__ and receive an unexpected type
2019-12-17 00:52:53	energizer	NotImplementedError is for what it says https://docs.python.org/3/library/exceptions.html#NotImplementedError
2019-12-17 00:53:01	client35	Ah, good to know
2019-12-17 00:53:31	client35	I read that already but let me read it again. Probably wasn't thinking clearly - it's late for me
