2019-12-17 12:19:07	dunpeal	thevishy: I'd recommend making a clear decision about what you care to learn.
2019-12-17 12:19:08	Widdershins	dunpeal: the reason python does this is so that indexing character points in the unicode string is always O(1). a lot of other languages drop this entirely and will store strings in utf-8 at the expense of character indexing becoming linear cost.
2019-12-17 12:19:17	Widdershins	er, codepoint indexing.
2019-12-17 12:19:23	<--	thorre (~thorre@90-230-32-217-no78.tbcn.telia.com) has quit (Quit: thorre)
2019-12-17 12:19:27	dunpeal	Widdershins: yes, it's always a space/time tradeoff.
2019-12-17 12:19:42	-->	youtah_ (~youtah@69.169.133.42) has joined #python
2019-12-17 12:19:44	FreeFull	Rust just doesn't have codepoint indexing at all
2019-12-17 12:19:51	Widdershins	i think the latter approach is better generally, since codepoint indexing is mostly worthless
2019-12-17 12:20:12	dunpeal	either you store everything as very wide bytes (sacrifice space), or you store as variable width (sacrifice time)
2019-12-17 12:20:18	FreeFull	Usually you want to do something like iterating over graphemes anyway
2019-12-17 12:20:20	-->	imdoor (~imdoor@balticom-142-78-50.balticom.lv) has joined #python
2019-12-17 12:20:32	dunpeal	Widdershins: yes, that's the Rust approach IIRC
2019-12-17 12:20:48	dunpeal	also there's hybrid approaches, like storing every 10th index in a lookup table
2019-12-17 12:20:58	<--	renlolo (~lhoward@pool-108-21-111-112.nycmny.fios.verizon.net) has quit (Ping timeout: 252 seconds)
